{
  "analysis": "The shell is open as root in /app. No MySQL interaction has been attempted yet. There is no visible output from any prior MySQL commands. Before asking or running any SQL, we need to determine whether a MySQL/MariaDB server is installed and running and whether a MySQL client is available so we can connect. The next steps are to inspect the filesystem for MySQL-related directories, check for running mysqld processes, and check for a mysql client binary and listening port (3306). After that, I'll be ready to accept your SQL question and run a single SQL statement as requested.",
  "plan": "1) Print current directory and list files to confirm environment. 2) Look for running MySQL/MariaDB processes. 3) Check whether a mysql client binary is available. 4) Check for MySQL data directory and socket directory (/var/lib/mysql and /var/run/mysqld). 5) Check listening ports for a service on 3306. Based on those results, I'll either attempt to connect (if client and server are available) or ask you for the database question and credentials. Each command is chosen to reveal whether MySQL is present and accessible.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "pwd\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ps aux | egrep 'mysqld|mariadbd' | egrep -v 'egrep' || true\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "mysql --version 2>&1 || true\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /var/lib/mysql 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /var/run/mysqld 2>/dev/null || true\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "ss -ltnp 2>/dev/null | egrep ':3306\\s|mysql|mysqld' || true\n",
      "duration": 0.5
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}

{
  "analysis": "Current environment: a root shell in /app. There are no files in /app. No mysqld/mariadbd processes are running. The mysql client is not installed (mysql: command not found). /var/lib/mysql and /var/run/mysqld are empty or do not exist, and nothing is listening on port 3306. Therefore I cannot run any SQL against a local MySQL server right now. To proceed I need either (A) access credentials for a remote MySQL server (host, port, user, password, database) so I can connect from a client, or (B) permission to install a MySQL client here and optionally start a local server. Before attempting installation, it’s useful to detect the OS and available package manager so I can choose the correct install commands.",
  "plan": "1) Detect the Linux distribution by reading /etc/os-release to decide how to install a client if you want me to. 2) Check whether apt-get or yum is available so I can propose an install command. After these checks I'll ask you whether you want me to (a) install a MySQL/MariaDB client (and possibly server) here, or (b) provide connection details for a remote database so I can run SQL there. If you choose installation, I'll proceed to install the client and then connect and run the single SQL statement you provide (one statement per your rules).",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cat /etc/os-release\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "which apt-get || which yum || which dnf || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}
